Nov 25 2009 	Charmed this jaded traveler	As a frequent business traveler, it's fun to stay in a non-big-chain hotel, when it works out. This time it did, and I'm glad. Montreal is so different from any other North American city I know, so I wanted us to stay somewhere that would remind us we weren't in Kansas. This place does the trick. It has an historic feel throughout, displaying many interesting relics from its past, some with narrative plaques. It's very intimate and cozy. There's one main inn, plus some lofts over a nice bar, where my friends stayed, just a city block away. My room was very spacious and clean, which can also be said of my friends' loft. Their loft could have slept 6 -- it had one bedroom, plus a sleeping area a few feet above a living room with a sofabed (I think). I could easily have crashed with them, except the loft/living room sleeping areas offered little privacy.You can see what the rooms look like from others' photos. I'll just add that mine was very clean, comfortable and quaint, if not ultra luxurious. It was a little too dark at night -- higher wattage bulbs, or at least a proper reading lamp would be a nice place to start, people. But my stay was relaxing, and the staff were ALL very friendly and polite and helpful to me. Hotels with character and charm typically have trade-offs. No A/C in the summer (if true) could be a problem. The front entrance is an awkward 3 stairs above the sidewalk. If Canada's accessibility laws are anything like ours, I assume they can accommodate wheels in the back entrance, which is on the charmingly cobblestoned and slightly touristy Rue St. Paul. By the way, the noise complaints are right. They should rename the above street Rue Bourbon; it is crunking loud, even on a cold November weeknight. The windows of this old hotel can keep out the weather, but not the shouting and singing. Easy solution: Request a room over the front of the building (port view), which will be much quieter. Not an option for me, because there happened to be renovation work on that side, but the ear plugs I remembered in my travel kit were enough to get me back to sleep. Nighttime revelers aside, we enjoyed the location. Chinatown restaurants and The Champ-de-Mars Metro station are just a 5-minute walk, although not in inclement weather. But Montreal is a proper city, with cabs (and rent-a-bikes, it would seem) on practically every corner.	
Nov 14 2009 	Very Disappointing Experience	I usually stay in downtown Montreal, but thought I would try the Old Port area for variety's sake and chose Auberge du Vieux-Port because it seemed like a nice place and good value. I selected a 'deluxe loft' suite which is not located in the main building, it was roughly a five minute walk from the hotel itself. What seemed chic and charming on their website was much less so in reality. The building itself was a beautiful old stone building, which was great looking on the outside. On the inside, access to the suite was only via a staircase - three flights up. There is no elevator, so be forewarned if you have a lot of bags, heavy bags, or have difficulty walking. The hallway to the suite itself also serves other suites that do not house hotel guests. I heard families coming and going and screaming in the halls at odd hours. The suite itself is large, has decent but not great furnishings and the condition was well below expectation. Maintenance was poor, and there was evidence of shoddy construction and upkeep. Walls are also quite thin, and because the sleeping portion of the loft itself hangs over the hallway, it was quite easy to hear everybody coming and going. Another problem is the design of the unit itself. Specifically the bathroom is on the main level and with the sleeping loft upstairs if you have to use the bathroom at night you must navigate a staircase in the dark. Very dangerous, in my opinion. Another problem related to temperature control in the suite. In short, there is no ability to control the temperature. There is a thermostat, but it is turned off and according to the hotel the temperature is regulated at the 'building' level, not the individual suite level. It happened to be quite warm, and because the windows were inoperable there was no way to cool it off. Also problematic is a huge industrial air duct located directly over the bed which is loud, cannot be shut off, blowing warm air 24/7. This is so loud it was literally impossible to sleep. When combined with the warm temperature in the suite itself it created a situation where I walked over to the main building at 2:30am and asked the hotel management if I could change rooms. Management was very accommodating, and at 3am I left the suite with my bags for a regular room in the main building. This regular room was much better, and consistent with what I expected. In summary, I would avoid the high priced suites and stay in the main building. But after this experience I'm not sure I would return. Also the internet connection in the room was unreliable and service was spotty.	
