Aug 11 2009 	A lot of room in a fun location - Vieux Port Lofts	My wife and I have traditionally stuck with brand name hotels - we just want to avoid the risk of finding ourselves miserable during our limited vacation time, especially for something we essentially have control over. We have two younger children, one 3 1/2 and the other seven months old, so we like extra space. We stayed at the Vieux Port Lofts, and we found there's an abundance of extra leg room. ABOUT THE HOTEL:Overall, the hotel has a nice atmosphere, and check in was easy with very friendly and accommodating staff. We arrived by taxi from the airport and loved the old cobblestone streets we had to drive through to get here. We know we're staying in tourist-central, but we have no pretense about being visitors and enjoying the charm of the old city. This hotel is right in the center of it all - the kitschy restaurants, post card shops...you name it.The lofts are not part of the hotel, but are a short walking distance away. Someone walked us and our bags over to our room. The one drawback with staying in the historic lofts and having small kids is there is no elevator, and there are lots of stairs. I wouldn't recommend this space if you're bringing the in-laws. (Mine would have complained, if they made it up them at all). Also, by staying in the lofts, there is no bellhop or doorman - you're given a set of keys to a nondescript entrance, and all you see are stairs (did I mention there were lots?).Overall, very helpful staff and concierge. Friendly and easy service through and through.ABOUT THE ROOM:We stayed in room 605, which is a true two bedroom with a very roomy living area (complete with DVD player, so pack those Dora episodes if you have them); there's also a small(er) kitchen, but it is a well laid out 1400 square feet of space... I have many friends with NYC apartments half the size of this place. The rooms are clean (although the kitchen and bathroom are a little dated - but this is more a nitpick since I was thrilled to have the kitchen amenities). The space is also charming, e.g. lots of exposed brick, lots of light, and we didn't have any noise issues (this is a response to previous posts I read on the hotel). I think the pictures of the furnishings on the hotel's website are a little misleading - the stuff feels more like you're staying in a Three-Star time share, as opposed to a swanky SoHo loft. Hotel staff had set up a pack and play for our little one. Also, we took advantage of the washer and dryer one floor below us. We stayed here for three nights, and overall - we loved it. When we return to Montreal, we'll look to stay here again. The space made this place feel like a home away from home - and the price was perfect. We're leaving tomorrow for Quebec City and are staying in a large suite at the Fairmont Hotel Frontenac. There, we're paying for one night what Vieux Port charged us for three. I can't wait to compare the value!	
Aug 10 2009 	Great Service Ruined by Early Morning Freight Train	My wife and I booked a room for a three night romantic getaway at the suggestion of friends. When we arrived, Frederick greeted us outside with a huge smile to help us unload the car. He was the best concierge we have ever had the pleasure of dealing with - always smiling, friendly, and ready to do whatever it takes. Whenever he saw us, he inquired about our visit, and asked if there was anything he could do. The front desk staff were equally helpful, assisting with restaurant recommendations/reservations and helping us plan a day exploring Montreal by subway, bus and foot. Valet parking included unlimited in/out privileges.We arrived just in time for the nightly wine and cheese guest reception in the restaurant. It is ticketed and each guest receives one generous glass of wine that can be taken to the tables outside on Rue de la Commune overlooking the port, or on the roof terrace. Additional glasses of wine are available for purchase.Everything was as advertised on the website. The room faced the port and had two large windows with twin glass panels that opened fully allowing cool fresh air in during the night. The bed was comfortable and was placed against an old brick wall. The bathroom was large with a pedestal sink (but the shower stall was quite small). There was a flat panel TV in the room, a CD player and mini speakers (the front desk has a library of CD's available to guests), and high speed wireless internet.We went to bed that first night very pleased with our choice.........until we were shaken from our sleep at 4:00 a.m. by the very loud squeaking, squealing, and screeching sounds of metal on metal coming from a slow moving freight train that was immediately across the street from the hotel and no more than 20 meters from our window. The train continued passing for 20 minutes, making sure that we were fully awake. It was like a scene straight out of the movie &quot;My Cousin Vinny.&quot; A second, shorter train came by at 6:00 a.m. just to make sure that our night's sleep was completely disturbed. This scenario repeated itself at the same time on each of the three nights we were there, preventing us from getting even one good night's sleep. It ruined what would have been an otherwise excellent stay. Perhaps a room on the other side of the hotel would have been a better choice, but we wanted a room with a view of the port. The hotel should warn guests of the potential for this considerable disturbance so that room location can be taken into account when making a reservation. If you want the room with a view and plan on sleeping through the night, you are well-advised to bring good earplugs.Bleary eyed from the lack of sleep, we made our way down to breakfast which is included with the room. There was a fine selection of hot and cold meals - the french toast was particularly good. Service at breakfast was a little spotty, but the food was tasty. If we return to Montreal, we will consider this hotel, but only if we can get a room facing Rue Saint Paul.	
